## Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

Successfully implemented Vercel Web Analytics for the Next.js App Router project.

### Changes Made

**1. Installed Dependencies:**
- Added `@vercel/analytics` package (v2.0.1) to dependencies
- Updated package-lock.json with new dependency tree

**2. Modified Files:**
- `src/app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics component to root layout
  - Imported `Analytics` component from `@vercel/analytics/next`
  - Added `<Analytics />` component at the end of the body, before the closing tag

### Implementation Details

Following the official Vercel Analytics documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), the Analytics component was integrated using the recommended approach for Next.js App Router:

1. The Analytics component is imported from `@vercel/analytics/next` (the Next.js-specific export)
2. Placed in the root layout file (`app/layout.tsx`) 
3. Added as the last child of the `<body>` element, after all other content

This placement ensures the Analytics component:
- Loads on all pages throughout the application
- Tracks page views and navigation
- Has minimal impact on page load performance (loads after content)

### Testing

- ✅ Build completed successfully (`npm run build`)
- ✅ Linter passed without errors (`npm run lint`)
- ✅ TypeScript compilation successful
- ✅ No runtime errors introduced

### Next Steps for Deployment

To activate Web Analytics on Vercel:
1. Deploy this code to Vercel
2. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard (Analytics → Enable)
3. Analytics data will start appearing after the next deployment

The tracking will work automatically once deployed to Vercel without requiring additional configuration.
